<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="51">
Fowler (1985a) described the differing habitat associations of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24745" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex lundii (Guérin-Méneville)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lundii">Acromyrmex lundii</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239665" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex pubescens" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubescens">Acromyrmex pubescens</taxonomicName>
, noting that the former is found in open habitats and the latter in the patchy forest “islands” that occur in the chaco savannah. The two forms are sympatric and structurally similar, both bearing elongate lateral pronotal spines that are longer than the mesonotal spines. However, these ants are distinguishable in pubescence. Much of the integument of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239665" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex pubescens" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubescens">A. pubescens</taxonomicName>
is covered in a dense decumbent pubescence while the integument of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24745" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex lundii (Guérin-Méneville)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lundi">A. lundi</taxonomicName>
is relatively bare. This difference is easiest to diagnose on the mesopleura, as the mesopleural pubescence of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239665" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex pubescens" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubescens">A. pubescens</taxonomicName>
comprises overlapping hairs, while that of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24745" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex lundii (Guérin-Méneville)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lundii">A. lundii</taxonomicName>
is sparse and the hairs non-overlapping. Given the ecological and morphological differences in sympatry between these two forms, I elevate 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239665" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex pubescens" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubescens">A. pubescens</taxonomicName>
to species here.
</paragraph>
